<TEXT>
New procedures for carry-on baggage could mean longer airport delays for
business travelers.
Stephanie Oswald explains in this "working ahead."
<TURN>
<ANNOTATION> Reporter: </ANNOTATION>
Some say the flying public needs a packing lesson.
<TURN>
You get some people trying to carry on a suitcase with everything but the
kitchen sink.
<TURN>
<ANNOTATION> Reporter: </ANNOTATION>
Business travelers often bring all their luggage on board in
order to avoid baggage claim and save time on the ground.
But when united airlines begins installing new stainless steel frames at
security checkpoints next month, the goal will be to stop bulky bags in
their path.
It's the latest in a long line of airline efforts designed to beat the
carry-on crunch.
<TURN>
Most business travelers probably are aware of what the policies are and
they'll deal with it, you know?
If we have to have a little smaller bag, we'll just maybe we just carry one
less shirt or something.
<TURN>
I can't carry it on?
<TURN>
no.
<TURN>
<ANNOTATION> Reporter: </ANNOTATION>
But experts worry about longer lines at security and a greater
fear -- lost luggage.
<TURN>
Lost luggage claims, since the airlines have cracked down on carry-on bags,
have gone up.
So over the last two or three months, we've seen more luggage lost.
So I think that the problem is only gonna get worse.
<TURN>
<ANNOTATION> Reporter: </ANNOTATION>
Continental is trying to find its solution on board -- new planes
will have larger overhead bins.
And the airline is retro-fitting current planes to make more room.
Stephanie Oswald, CNN, reporting.
</TEXT>
